<BaseLayout
  title="What Catalog Ownership Means | How Much Music"
  description="A practical explanation of masters, publishing, and catalog-sale economics."
  type="article"
>
  <section>
    <p class="eyebrow">Explainer</p>
    <h1>What catalog ownership means</h1>
    <p>
      The gross revenue earned by a song is not the same as the amount an artist or estate keeps.
      Catalog ownership determines where money lands before it reaches the performer, writer, or heirs.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Core layers</h2>
    <ul class="meta-list">
      <li><strong>Masters:</strong> The sound recording side, often controlled by a label or catalog buyer.</li>
      <li><strong>Publishing:</strong> The composition side, split across writers and publishers.</li>
      <li><strong>Catalog sales:</strong> An artist may have already exchanged future revenue for an upfront payout.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What changes the artist-side number</h2>
    <ul class="meta-list">
      <li>A performer who also wrote the song may participate in both master-side and publishing-side income.</li>
      <li>A label-controlled master can leave the artist with a smaller share than the gross recording revenue suggests.</li>
      <li>An estate or catalog buyer can receive future income if rights were sold or transferred.</li>
      <li>A song with strong sync value can produce income that is not visible from streaming popularity alone.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Why the split matters</h2>
    <p>
      Two catalogs can generate similar gross revenue while delivering very different artist-side
      outcomes. Contract history and ownership structure matter as much as raw popularity.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is why gross revenue, artist-side share, label share, publishing share, and writer share
      should stay separate when the available context supports that split.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>How to read ownership notes</h2>
    <ul class="meta-list">
      <li>Treat ownership notes as context for the modeled range, not as a complete contract history.</li>
      <li>Look for whether the page separates master and publishing value.</li>
      <li>Give more weight to pages with public ownership or catalog-sale references than pages with platform links alone.</li>
      <li>Use the contact page if a rights note needs correction or a better public source.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
